definition.value: A hydrate obtained by combining oxyphenbutazone with one molar equivalent of water. Commonly used to treat pain, swelling and stiffness associated with arthritis and gout, it was withdrawn from the market 1984 following association with blood dyscrasis and Stevens-Johnson syndrome.

An aromatic amino acid that is 2-amino-5-ethylphenylacetic acid in which one of the amino hydrogens is replaced by a 2,3,5,6-tetrafluorophenyl group. A selective cyclooxygenase 2 inhibitor that is used in veterinary medicine for the relief of pain and inflammation in cats and dogs.
A dicarboxylic acid dianion obtained by deprotonation of both carboxy groups of suberic acid; major species at pH 7.3.
A dicarboxylic acid dianion obtained by deprotonation of both carboxy groups of suberic acid; major species at pH 7.3.

A member of the class of chloroethanes that is ethane in which five of the six hydrogens are replaced by chlorines. A non-flammable, high-boiling liquid (b.p. 161-162degreeC) with relative density 1.67 and an odour resembling that of chloroform, it is used as a solvent for oil and grease, in metal cleaning, and in the separation of coal from impurities.
A hydroxy fatty acid anion obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group of any omega-hydroxy fatty acid; major species at pH 7.3.
An alpha,omega-dicarboxylic acid that is tetradecane in which the methyl groups have been oxidised to the corresponding carboxylic acids.
A hydroxy fatty acid anion obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group of any omega-oxo fatty acid; major species at pH 7.3.
An alpha,omega-dicarboxylic acid that is docosane in which the methyl groups have been oxidised to the corresponding carboxylic acids.
An alpha,omega-dicarboxylic acid that is hexacosane in which the methyl groups have been oxidised to the corresponding carboxylic acids.
Any glycosyloxyflavone that is an O-glycosylated derivative of quercetin.
A nitroso compound that is any urea in which one of the nitrogens is substituted by a nitroso group
Any unsaturated fatty acid anion containing more than one C-C unsaturated bond.  Major species at pH 7.3.
Any lipid that is glycerol bearing two substituent groups - either acyl, alkyl, or alk-1-enyl - at any two of the three possible positions.
A polyene macrolide antibiotic; part of the nystatin complex produced by several Streptococcus species. The keto-form of nystatin A1.
A 3-hydroxy fatty acid anion that is the conjugate base of 3-hydroxylauric acid, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
An omega-hydroxy fatty acid anion that is the conjugate base of 3,12-dihydroxylauric acid, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
A fatty acid anion obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group of any omega-methyl fatty acid; major species at pH 7.3.

An amino acid betaine that is ergothioneine in which the hydrogen attached to the sulfur is replaced by a methyl group. It has been isolated from the deepwater (500-1,600 m) marine sponge Macandrewia azorica.
A hydroxy fatty acid anion that is the conjugate base of 11-hydroxylauric acid, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
Any member of the class of lysophosphatidic acids which has a free hydroxy group at the 2-position of the glycerol moiety.
Any member of the class of lysophosphatidic acids which has a free hydroxy group at the 1-position of the glycerol moiety.
Any eukaryotic metabolite produced during a metabolic reaction in plants, the kingdom that include flowering plants, conifers and other gymnosperms.
A fatty acid anion obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group of any 2,3-saturated fatty acid.
An alpha,omega-dicarboxylic acid that is (5Z,8Z,11Z,14Z)-icosatetraene in which the two methyl groups are replaced by carboxy groups.
Any prokaryotic metabolite produced during a metabolic reaction in bacteria.
A macrolide antibiotic that is 20-oxotylactone having a 5-O-beta-D-mycaminosyl residue attached at position 6.
A macrolide antibiotic that is tylonolide having a beta-D-mycaminosyl residue attached at position 5.
A cyclic peptide antibiotic that is A47934 lacking the O-sulfo group; it is produced by a strain of Streptomyces toyocaensis.
A branched-chain saturated fatty acid anion that is nonanoate with methyl branches at C-4 and C-8. Major species at pH 7.3.
An amino disaccharide consisting of N-acetyl-beta-D-galactosamine having a beta-D-tyvelosyl residue attached at the 3-position and with the anomeric hydroxy group replaced by methoxy.
An amino disaccharide consisting of beta-D-galactosamine having a beta-D-tyvelosyl residue attached at the 3-position and with the anomeric hydroxy group replaced by methoxy.
An amino disaccharide consisting of N-acetyl-6-O-methyl-beta-D-galactosamine having a beta-D-tyvelosyl residue attached at the 3-position and with the anomeric hydroxy group replaced by methoxy.
An amino disaccharide consisting of N-acetyl-beta-D-galactosamine having a 2-O-methyl-beta-D-tyvelosyl residue attached at the 3-position and with the anomeric hydroxy group replaced by methoxy.
An amino disaccharide consisting of 6-O-methyl-beta-D-galactosamine having a beta-D-tyvelosyl residue attached at the 3-position and with the anomeric hydroxy group replaced by methoxy.
An amino disaccharide consisting of 6-O-methyl-beta-D-galactosamine having a 2-O-methyl-beta-D-tyvelosyl residue attached at the 3-position and with the anomeric hydroxy group replaced by methoxy.
A monohydroxycinnamic acid that is cinnamic acid in which the phenyl hydrogens at positions 3, 4, and 5 are replaced by methoxy, hydroxy, and methoxy groups, respectively.
A dye used in microscopic or electron microscopic examination of cells and tissues to give contrast and to highlight particular features of interest, such as nuclei and cytoplasm.
Phenol substituted with iodo and nitro groups at the 3 and 5 positions respectively.
A methyl glycoside that is alpha-L-Fucp-(1->3)-[beta-D-Galp-(1->4)]-beta-D-GlcpNAc (Le(x)) in which the hydroxy group at the reducing-end anomeric centre is methylated.

A methyl glycoside that is alpha-L-Fucp-(1->3)-[beta-D-Galp-(1->4)]-beta-D-GlcpNAc (Le(x)) in which the galactose residue is 4-dehydroxylated and the hydroxy group at the reducing-end anomeric centre is methylated.

A methyl glycoside that is alpha-L-Fucp-(1->3)-[beta-D-Galp-(1->4)]-beta-D-GlcpNAc (Le(x)) in which the galactose 4-OH is replaced by chlorine and the hydroxy group at the reducing-end anomeric centre is methylated.

A methyl glycoside that is alpha-L-Fucp-(1->3)-[beta-D-Galp-(1->4)]-beta-D-GlcpNAc (Le(x)) in which the galactose 4-OH is replaced by fluorine and the hydroxy group at the reducing-end anomeric centre is methylated.
A 1-acyl-2-arachidonoyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphate in which the 1-acyl group is specified as stearoyl (octadecanoyl).
A 1-acyl-2-arachidonoyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphate in which the 1-acyl group is specified as arachidoyl (icosanoyl).
A 1-acyl-2-linoleoyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphate in which the 1-acyl group is specified as stearoyl (octadecanoyl).
A 1-acyl-2-arachidonoyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphate in which the 1-acyl group is also arachidonoyl.
A 1-acyl-2-linoleoyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphate in which the 1-acyl group is also linoleoyl.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycerol 3-phosphate in which the acyl substituents at positions 1 and 2 are specified as stearoyl and (4Z,7Z,10Z,13Z,16Z,19Z)-docosahexaenoyl respectively.
An alkanesulfonic acid obtained by the formal substitution of one of the methyl hydrogens of propane-1,2-diol by a sulfonic acid group.
